  "prompt": "What could cause your period to be 14 days late other than pregnancy?",
  "response": "Okay, a late period can be stressful, and it's natural to jump to the conclusion of pregnancy. However, there are many other reasons why your period might be delayed. Here's a breakdown of potential causes, aside from pregnancy:\n\n**Lifestyle Factors:**\n\n*   **Stress:** This is a big one. Stress can significantly impact your hormones and disrupt your menstrual cycle. This includes emotional stress, work stress, or even physical stress.\n*   **Significant Weight Changes:** Both gaining and losing a lot of weight quickly can affect hormone levels and lead to irregular periods.\n*   **Changes in Exercise Routine:** Starting a new intense exercise program or significantly increasing your workout intensity can sometimes disrupt your cycle, especially if you're also restricting calories.\n*   **Dietary Changes/Poor Nutrition:** Drastic dietary changes or not eating enough nutrients can disrupt your hormones.\n\n**Medical Conditions:**\n\n*   **Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS):** This hormonal disorder is a common cause of irregular periods. Other symptoms may include acne, excess hair growth, and weight gain.\n*   **Thyroid Issues:** Both hypothyroidism (underactive thyroid) and hyperthyroidism (overactive thyroid) can affect your menstrual cycle.\n*   **Premature Ovarian Insufficiency (POI):** This condition, also known as early menopause, causes the ovaries to stop working properly before the age of 40.\n*   **Uterine Problems:** Scarring of the uterine lining can sometimes affect bleeding.\n\n**Medications:**\n\n*   **Hormonal Birth Control:** Starting, stopping, or changing hormonal birth control methods (pills, patch, ring, IUD) can definitely affect your cycle's regularity. It can take a few months for your body to adjust.\n*   **Other Medications:** Certain medications, such as antidepressants, antipsychotics, and corticosteroids, can sometimes interfere with your menstrual cycle.\n\n**Other Factors:**\n\n*   **Breastfeeding:** Breastfeeding can delay the return of your period after childbirth.\n*   **Perimenopause:** As you approach menopause, your periods may become irregular and unpredictable.\n*   **Chronic Illness:** Long-term illnesses, such as diabetes, celiac disease, or inflammatory bowel disease, can sometimes affect your menstrual cycle.\n\n**When to See a Doctor:**\n\nIt's generally a good idea to see a doctor if:\n\n*   Your period is consistently irregular.\n*   You've missed three or more periods in a row.\n*   You have other symptoms, such as pelvic pain, heavy bleeding, or unusual discharge.\n*   You are concerned about the possibility of pregnancy, even if you've had a negative pregnancy test.\n*   You have any other concerns about your menstrual health.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Track Your Cycle:** Keeping a record of your periods (using a period tracker app or calendar) can help you identify patterns and notice any changes.\n*   **Don't Self-Diagnose:** It's important to see a doctor for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.\n*   **Be Open With Your Doctor:** Provide your doctor with a complete medical history and be honest about your lifestyle habits.\n\nI hope this information is helpful. Remember, I am an AI and cannot provide medical advice. It's always best to consult with a healthcare professional for any concerns about your health.\n",
